[src:fred-corey/1885-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1885 throughout the world.
[src:fred-corey/1885-in-baseball] Post-season playoff: the Chicago White Stockings played the St.
[src:fred-corey/1885-in-baseball] Louis Browns, which ended with both teams going 3–3–1 in a best-of-seven series.
[src:fred-corey/1885-in-baseball] Game 1 finished in a tie called after eight innings due to darkness; Game 2 was awarded to Chicago by forfeit after six innings because St.
[src:fred-corey/1885-in-baseball] Louis refused to continue after disputing an umpiring decision.
[src:fred-corey/1885-in-baseball] Both teams dispute the series and claim the championship.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The **American Association of Base Ball Clubs** (**AA**) was a professional baseball league that existed for 10 seasons from 1882 to 1891.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Together with the National League (NL), founded in 1876, the AA participated in an early version of the World Series seven times versus the champion of the NL in an interleague championship playoff tournament.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] At the end of its run, several AA franchises joined the NL.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] After 1891, the NL existed alone, with each season's champions being awarded the Temple Cup (1894–1897).
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] During its existence, the AA was often simply referred to as "the Association" in the media, in contrast to the NL, which was sometimes called "the League".
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] It was also sometimes called the "Beer and Whiskey League".
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The American Association (AA) distinguished itself in several ways from what it considered to be the puritanical National League (NL).
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The new league established teams in what the NL leaders pejoratively called "river cities", including Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Louisville and St.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Louis, with the inherent implication of lower morality or social standards in those cities.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] In contrast to the NL, the AA offered cheaper ticket prices, Sunday games and alcoholic beverages to its patrons.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] On November 8, 1881, at the Gibson House in Cincinnati, it was decided that individual teams in the league-to-be would operate their own affairs and set their own admission prices, under an agreement called the "guarantee system".
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The NL at that time prohibited the sale of alcohol on its grounds, while the AA had no such restrictions, especially as several of its teams were backed by breweries and distilleries.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The AA became known as "The Beer and Whiskey League", another pejorative term applied by NL owners, which did not seem to bother the fans of the Association's clubs.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Beginning in 1884 and continuing through 1890, the champion of the AA met the champion of the NL in an early version of the World Series.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] These early Series were less organized than the modern version, with as few as three games played and as many as fifteen, and the contests of 1885 and 1890 ending in disputed ties.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The NL won four of these Series, while the AA won only one, in 1886 when the St.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Louis Cardinals) defeated the Chicago White Stockings (now the Chicago Cubs).
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Over its lifetime, the AA was weakened by several factors.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] One was the tendency of some of its teams to jump to the NL.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The consistently stronger NL was in better position to survive adverse conditions.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Some owners of AA teams also owned a NL team.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The most significant blow to the AA was dealt by the Players' League, a third major league formed in 1890, which siphoned off talent and gate receipts.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] In a rare historical oddity, the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (now the Los Angeles Dodgers) won the league's championship and represented the AA in the 1889 World Series, switched to the NL during the off-season, and then repeated the same feat.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] No player who spent the majority of his career in the AA is in the baseball Hall of Fame, although Bid McPhee of the Cincinnati Reds played eight of his eighteen seasons in the AA before the Reds moved to the National League.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The living legacy of the old Association is the group of teams that came over to the National League to stay.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The Pirates moved to the NL after the 1886 season, the Bridegrooms/Dodgers and the Cincinnati Reds after the 1889 season, and the Browns/Cardinals after the American Association folded following the 1891 season.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Following the reorganization and contraction of the NL from 12 teams down to 8 in 1900, half of the eight surviving teams were former members of the AA.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Several of the AA's home-field venues survived into the 1960s: The ballpark used by the 1891 Washington club evolved into Griffith Stadium; the home of the St.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns, Sportsman's Park; and the city block occupied by the Reds, which evolved into Crosley Field.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Other than the clubs themselves, Crosley Field was the last physical remnant of the AA—it was the home field of the Cincinnati Reds until mid-season 1970 and was razed in April 1972.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] During the AA's existence, four clubs defected over to the NL: Allegheny City (joined NL 1887, later became the Pittsburgh Pirates), the Cleveland Spiders (joined NL 1889), the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (joined NL 1890, eventually renamed the Dodgers), and the Cincinnati Reds (joined NL 1890).
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] At the AA's demise in 1891, four additional clubs joined the NL: the St.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns (later the Cardinals), the Louisville Colonels, the Washington Statesmen (renamed the Senators), and the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] Therefore, from 1892 to 1899, when the NL consisted of 12 teams, 8 of them had been former AA clubs.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] All four have posted more than 10,000 all-time major-league victories.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] AA statistics are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB), the AA being one of six leagues deemed "major" by the Special Baseball Records Committee of Major League Baseball in 1969.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The first line is the formation of the American Association (AA) in 1882, and the second marks the end of the American Association.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] World's Championship Series championships are shown with a "•", American Association Pennants in non-World Championship Series seasons are shown with a "#", and American Association Pennant winners who tied or lost the World Championship Series are shown with a "^".
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] For the 1891 season, the Philadelphia Athletics were replaced by the Philadelphia Quakers of the Player's League.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] The 1891 Cincinnati Kelly's Killers folded during the season and were replaced by the Milwaukee Brewers.
[src:fred-corey/american-association-19th-century] All non-American Association labels not labeled "NL" (National League) or "PL" (Players' League) are minor league teams.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:fred-corey/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
